    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Project started in 2015.

1. Number of new technologies transferred to Bosnia and Herzegovina as part of a methodology for strategic flood risk management.
2. Vrbas river basin (12% of BiH territory) covered by an automated hydrometric monitoring network for effective Flood Forecasting and Early Warning.
3. Policy environment and regulatory framework for adaptation related technology transfer established or strengthened
4. Strengthened Capacity to transfer appropriate adaptation technologies
5. Number of institutions enabled to modify risk management strategies  based on introduced vulnerability, loss and damages assessment and improved hydrometric monitoring technologies  
6. Number of people in target basin benefiting from flood risk management adaptation technologies, tools, and adaptation strategies, and are less exposed to flood risk
7. Availability of innovative non-structural measures introduced and implemented as part of climate adaptation strategies to provide improved resilience to communities (include agric.  
8. Number of communities benefitting from introduced forecasting, early warning, response and recovery technologies to support local communities at risk of flooding</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2015">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">Project started in 2015.

1. 0 strategic flood risk management technologies in Bosnia and Herzegovina 
2. No automatized and centralized hydrometric network in Vrbas river basin
3. No policy/regulatory framework for adaptation related technology transfer in place
4. Local professionals are unaware of adaptation technologies
5. Most of the socio-economic information required to assess flood damages, losses, exposure and vulnerability is not currently available and is not collected systematically and gender-disaggregation of data not systematically done.
6.Current approach limited of inclusion of local communities, and particularly the vulnerable groups
7.Current approach to flood risk management is structural flood protection measures and non-structural measures are not considered to be adaptive measure.
8. 0 communities benefitting from introduced forecasting, early warning, response and recovery technologies to support local communities at risk of flooding.</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Finalize flood risk management plan.
2. Establish Flood forecasting and early warning system for Vrbas river basin
3. Develop GIS based loss/damage model for housing, business and agricultural sectors
4.0
5.0
6. 250,000 people in target basin benefiting from flood risk management adaptation technologies, tools, and adaptation strategies, and are less exposed to flood risk
7. Implement at least 2 non-structural flood risk management measures 
8. 14 communities benefitting from introduced forecasting, early warning, response and recovery technologies to support local communities at risk of flooding</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Flood risk management plan developed and accepted by Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Water Management RS
2. Flood forecasting and early warning system for Vrbas river basin developed and tested
3. GIS based loss/damage model for housing, business and agricultural sectors developed and incorporated in GIS tool (Vrbas GeoPortal)
4. 0.
5. 0
6.Flood risk management adaptation technologies, tools, and adaptation strategies applied in Vrbas basin and ensured flood risk reduction and benefits for 250,000 inhabitants of the basin
7. Twelve (12) Non-structural flood risk management measures implemented in Vrbas basin (total 21 measure in 12 municipalities)
8. Flood forecasting, early warning, response and recovery technologies implemented in 14 municipalities to support local communities at risk of flooding (early warning system developed, response communication improved, response and recovery improved by raising knowledge and information on floods (over 600 participants at various trainings)</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
